@page "/impact"

<section class="impact-hero">
    <h1>Our Impact (Conceptual)</h1>
    <p>
        Ripple is a proof‑of‑concept project created for a college honors program. While the website 
        models how a real aquaponics‑based nonprofit could address food insecurity in Chicagoland, 
        Ripple is not an active organization. This page illustrates the potential impact such a system 
        could have if implemented in a real community setting.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="impact-section">
    <h2>Food Insecurity in Chicago</h2>
    <p>
        Many Chicago‑area households face rising food costs, limited access to fresh produce, and 
        structural barriers that contribute to food insecurity. These challenges make the region an 
        ideal case study for exploring sustainable, year‑round food production models.
    </p>
    <p>
        In this project, Ripple is used as a hypothetical example of how aquaponics could help close 
        this gap by producing fresh, nutrient‑dense food locally and consistently.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="impact-section">
    <h2>How Ripple Helps (Modeled Impact)</h2>

    <div class="impact-grid">
        <div class="impact-card">
            <h3>Year‑Round Food Production</h3>
            <p>
                The conceptual aquaponics system grows leafy greens and tilapia continuously, 
                demonstrating how controlled‑environment agriculture can operate regardless of season.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="impact-card">
            <h3>Local Distribution</h3>
            <p>
                In this model, food is distributed through food pantries, shelters, and community 
                partners. This distribution network is hypothetical and included to show how a real 
                nonprofit might serve neighborhoods facing food insecurity.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="impact-card">
            <h3>Sustainable Farming</h3>
            <p>
                Aquaponics uses up to <strong>90% less water</strong>, requires no soil, and minimizes 
                chemical inputs. These sustainability benefits are part of the system design explored 
                in this academic project.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="impact-card">
            <h3>Community Engagement</h3>
            <p>
                Volunteers, students, and local residents are imagined as participants in planting, 
                harvesting, packaging, and outreach. These roles are conceptual and demonstrate how 
                community involvement could look in a real implementation.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="impact-card">
            <h3>Education & Research</h3>
            <p>
                The project includes a modeled research area to illustrate how innovation in aquaponics 
                could be supported and shared with the broader community.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="impact-section">
    <h2>Environmental Impact (Conceptual)</h2>
    <p>
        Aquaponics reduces environmental strain by conserving water, reducing land use, lowering carbon 
        footprint, minimizing chemical inputs, and supporting biodiversity. The project also models 
        features like skylights, efficient LED lighting, and energy‑saving design choices to demonstrate 
        how a real facility might operate sustainably.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="impact-section">
    <h2>Building a More Resilient Future</h2>
    <p>
        While aquaponics is not a full replacement for traditional agriculture, it offers a powerful 
        supplement — especially in urban environments. By producing food locally, sustainably, and 
        predictably, systems like the one modeled in Ripple could help communities become more resilient 
        to climate change, supply chain disruptions, rising food costs, and seasonal shortages.
    </p>
</section>
